We are developing a set of microservices that derives geographic position from star sighting information. Each microservice receives its input as a Python dictionary represented by a URL-encoded string and outputs its result as UTF-8 string of a Python dictionary. This assignment has you to write a function that adjusts celestial sightings based on the circumstances of how the sighting was made.

ss:Data.Font: performs a specific navigational calculation based on information it receives via its parameters.

Cell.Data: Performs the calculation named by the 'op' dictionary key. Returns a dictionary containing the results. Calculations are:

Adjusts the celestial sighting according to amospheric conditions
Angle of the sighting relative to a reference point. This angle is referred to as the "observed altitude". It is a mandatory string in the form xdy.y where
x is the degree portion of the altitude. It is a postive integer .GE. 0 and .LT. 90
d is the character "d" and used to separate degrees from minutes
y.y is the minute portion of the altitude. It is a positive floating point value with one digit to the right of the decimal point and is in the range .GE. 0.0 and .LT. 60.0.
Height (in feet) at which the observation was made. It is a string of a numeric value .GE. 0. Optional, deaults to '0' if missing.
Temperature (in degrees F) at the time of the observation. It is a string of an integer in the range .GE. -20 and .LE. 120. Optional, defaults to '72' if missing.
Barometric pressure (in mbar) at the time of the observation. It is a string of an integer in the range .GE. 100 and .LE. 1100. Optional, defaults to '1010' if missing.
What the observed altitude is relative to. It is one of the following case-insensitive strings: "artificial" or "natural". Optional, defaults to "natural" if missing.
Dictionary elements not specified above are ignored.
